    <section id="The_parts_of_speech" >
      <title>The parts of speech</title>
    </section>
    <section id="The_grammatical_codes" >
      <title>The grammatical codes</title>
      <p>All the words are analysed with dictionary form + grammatical tags. Each tag is introduced with a &quot;+&quot; sign. We thus have</p>
      <p>biila+N+Sg+Acc<br/>boahtit+V+Ind+Prs+Sg1</p>
      <p>At the moment, the following multicharacter symbols are defined in the lexicon file:</p>
      <source>Multichar_Symbols
 +N +A +Adv +V
 +Pron +CS +CC +Adp +Po +Pr +Interj +Pcle
 +Pers +Dem +Interr +Refl +Recipr +Rel +Indef
 +Ess +Sg +Pl +Nom +Gen +Acc +Ill +Loc +Com
 +PxSg1 +PxSg2 +PxSg3 +PxDu1 +PxDu2 +PxDu3 +PxPl1 +PxPl2 +PxPl3
 +Comp +Superl +Actor
 +Clt +Attr
 +Pass +Ind +Prs +Prt +Pot +Cond +Imprt
 +Sg1 +Sg2 +Sg3 +Du1 +Du2 +Du3 +Pl1 +Pl2 +Pl3
 +Inf +Act +Ger +ConNeg +Neg +ImprtII +PrsPrc +PrfPrc +VGen +VAbess
 X1 X2 X3 X4 X5 X6 X7 X8 X9 Y1 Y2 Y3 Y4 Y5 Y6 Y7 Y8 Q1 Q2 Q3 Q4 Q5 Q6 Q7 Q8 Q9
 a1 e1 c1 d1 i1 n1 o1 s1 t1 u1 z1 g2 h2 m2 n2
</source>
      <p>These are the main POS:</p>
      <p>Nouns, adjectives, verbs, pronouns, adverbs, particles, subjunctions, conjunctions, adpositions, postpositions, prepositions and interjections.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="The_nouns" >
      <title>The nouns</title>
      <p>The string is &quot;+N+Number+Case+Possessivesuffix+Clitic&quot;. The word form &quot;biilasgo&quot; is thus analysed as &quot;biila+N+Sg+Gen+PxSg3+Clt&quot;.</p>
      <p>Here is a list of the nominal tags, given in the same order as for the analysis. Note that the grammatical categories in parentheses can be omitted.</p>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <td>Part of speech:</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Number:</td>
          <td>+Sg, +Pl</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Case:</td>
          <td>+Ess +Nom +Gen +Acc +Ill +Loc +Com</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Possessive suffix:)</td>
          <td>+PxSg1 +PxSg2 +PxSg3 +PxDu1 +PxDu2 +PxDu3 +PxPl1 +PxPl2 +PxPl3</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Clitic:)</td>
          <td>+Clt</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>
    <section id="The_adjectives" >
      <title>The adjectives</title>
      <p>Used non-attributively the adjective resembles the noun:</p>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <td>Part of speech:</td>
          <td>+A</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Grade:)</td>
          <td>+Comp, +Superl</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Number:</td>
          <td>+Sg, +Pl</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Case:</td>
          <td>+Ess +Nom +Gen +Acc +Ill +Loc +Com</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Clitic:)</td>
          <td>+Clt</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <p>Used attributively the adjective has a quite simple tag scheme:</p>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <td>Part of speech:</td>
          <td>+A</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Attribute</td>
          <td>+Attr</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Clitic:)</td>
          <td>+Clt</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>
    <section id="The_verbs" >
      <title>The verbs</title>
      <p>Finite and infinite verb forms have quite distinct paradigms. Finite first:</p>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <td>Part of speech:</td>
          <td>+V</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Derivation)</td>
          <td>+Pass</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Mood:</td>
          <td>+Ind, +Pot, +Cond, +Imprt</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Tense</td>
          <td>+Prs, +Prt</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Person/Number</td>
          <td>+Sg1 +Sg2 +Sg3 +Du1 +Du2 +Du3 +Pl1 +Pl2 +Pl3, +ConNeg</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Clitic:</td>
          <td>+Clt</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <p>Infinite verb forms:</p>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <td>Part of speech:</td>
          <td>+V</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Derivation:)</td>
          <td>+Pass</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Nominal verb form</td>
          <td>+Inf, +Act, +Ger, +PrsPrc, +PrfPrc, +VGen, +VAbess</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Clitic:)</td>
          <td>+Clt</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <p>Other derived verb forms:</p>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <td>Part of speech:</td>
          <td>+V</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Part of speech:</td>
          <td>+N</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Derivation</td>
          <td>+Actor</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Number</td>
          <td>+Sg, +Pl</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Case:</td>
          <td>+Ess +Nom +Gen +Acc +Ill +Loc +Com</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Possessive suffix:)</td>
          <td>+PxSg1 +PxSg2 +PxSg3 +PxDu1 +PxDu2 +PxDu3 +PxPl1 +PxPl2 +PxPl3</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>(Clitic:)</td>
          <td>+Clt</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <p>Here is an example: &quot;addit&quot; > addit+V+N+Actor+Pl+Nom</p>
      <p>These tags are still not documented: +Act +Neg +ImprtII</p>
    </section>
    <section id="The_pronouns" >
      <title>The pronouns</title>
      <p>The personal, demonstrative and interrogative pronouns:</p>
      <p>baseform+Pron+Pers+Number+Case</p>
      <p>Example:</p>
      <p>mun+Pron+Pers+Sg+Com<br/>dat+Pron+Dem+Pl+Nom</p>
      <p>The reflexive pronouns:</p>
      <p>baseform+Pron+pronoun_type+Case(+possessive suffix)</p>
      <p>Example: ies1+Pron+Refl+Loc+PxDu1</p>
    </section>
    <section id="The_Incdeclinable_words" >
      <title>The Incdeclinable words</title>
      <p>These have their POS tag as their only tag:</p>
